    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "### Problem\n\ndebounce_text_changes doesn't do anything these days, and hasn't for quite a while (goes back to at least 0.10). This causes high CPU usage (and thus excessive battery drain) with some language servers, notably lua-language-server.\n\nThe main cause is vim.lsp.semantic_tokens and vim.lsp.document_color, both of which are enabled by default and both of which trigger sending didChange on (almost) every keystroke.\n\nvim.lsp.semantic_tokens happens to have [a debounce mechanism](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/6780e78b0981f52aec9c4ef96356d3fef3742c9a/runtime/lua/vim/lsp/semantic_tokens.lua#L776-L782), but there doesn't seem to be any way to actually configure it from a user's init.lua.\nvim.lsp.document_color has no debounce whatsoever and will issue didChange on literally every single letter typed.\n\nThe following issue seems relevant but it was closed as completed without addressing the actual debounce issue itself:\n* https://github.com/neovim/neovim/issues/32277\n\n### Steps to reproduce using \"nvim --clean -u minimal_init.lua\"\n\nminimal_init.lua:\n```lua\nvim.lsp.config('lua_ls', {\n        cmd = { 'lua-language-server' },\n        filetypes = { 'lua' },\n        flags = { debounce_text_changes = 5000 },\n})\nvim.lsp.enable('lua_ls')\n-- vim.lsp.semantic_tokens.enable(false)\n-- vim.lsp.document_color.enable(false)\n```\n\n1. `nvim --clean -u minimal_init.lua runtime/lua/editorconfig.lua` (or any other lua file)\n2. wait a lil bit for lua-language-server to start\n3. enter insert mode and start typing (random gibberish in a comment will do)\n4. run `top` in another terminal and observe that lua-l-s keeps using 50+% CPU\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nI'd expect debounce_text_changes to affect vim.lsp.semantic_tokens and vim.lsp.document_color and actually debounce the sending of didChange requests to the language server.\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\nv0.12.2\n\n### Language server name/version\n\nlua-language-server 3.18.2\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nDebian testing\n\n### Log file\n\nN/A",
